But today I want to talk about another
way to distribute your business apps

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:20.090
that you may not have heard about.

00:02:20.350 --> 00:02:23.050
It's called Custom B2B.

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:26.040
So let's talk about
that for a few minutes.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:31.940
Custom B2B apps are apps that are
tailor-made for a specific client.

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:37.030
They are available exclusively
to clients that you select.

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:37.830
All right?

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:39.550
Let me say that again.

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:43.800
You can make these apps
available only to select clients.

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:47.900
They are available for
purchase exclusively through

00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:49.840
the Volume Purchas program.

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:52.530
And we'll talk about
that program in a minute.

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:56.640
And they're hosted by Apple.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:59.800
So you don't have to think
about how to distribute this.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:05.670
We take care of the distribution
and hosting for you.

00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:11.140
Let's look at some examples
of what B2B apps can be.

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:13.690
Here's an App Store app.

00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:31.800
[Transcript missing]

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:36.040
You can make one of these
apps for a specific client.

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:41.810
It may not be suitable for the App Store,
but it certainly is very powerful

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:44.230
for the client that you're serving.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:46.370
Here's another example.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:51.980
This is a sales catalog or
a product catalog here for a

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:54.860
heavy equipment manufacturer.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:57.680
You know,
you can tap a button to watch a video,

00:03:57.690 --> 00:04:00.590
you can get a brochure
mailed to yourself,

00:04:00.590 --> 00:04:00.800
et cetera.

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:07.360
With a bit of customization and skinning,
you can turn this app into a sales tool

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:10.340
for a completely unrelated industry.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:15.900
Custom colors, custom parts, etc.

00:04:16.630 --> 00:04:18.180
Another example.

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:20.540
Here's an interesting one.

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:24.830
So we have a manufacturer
of power equipment.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.220
And they have independent distributors.

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:32.170
And they want their distributors to have
an app that shows them the latest parts

00:04:32.170 --> 00:04:35.170
catalog with a great amount of detail.

00:04:35.180 --> 00:04:38.070
This is a proprietary
database that they have.

00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:42.430
And this is a great way to deliver
parts information to their distributors.

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:45.670
But they don't want to make
this available in the app store.

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:49.190
And they can't really use the
enterprise in-house program

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:53.180
because their distributors are
not part of their enterprise.

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:55.920
So B2B apps are great for this.

00:04:55.960 --> 00:04:57.840
They make an app for B2B.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:00.760
They allow the distributors
to download it.

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:03.280
And we distribute it to them.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:04.980
Very convenient.

00:05:08.330 --> 00:05:09.900
Here's another example.

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:16.740
This is a nurse station application,
maybe at a hospital or a clinic.

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:22.640
When you target an app towards a
specific industry like healthcare,

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:27.900
there are peculiar concerns to that
industry that you need to take care of,

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:33.590
such as privacy, data protection,
policies, and so forth.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:36.060
may not be a good fit
for the store maybe,

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:37.820
but great fit for a B2B app.

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:44.900
You can solve a particular niche
industry's concerns with your app.

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:48.860
And one final example,
here's a really cool app.

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:52.560
This app delivers papers
for board meetings.

00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:54.900
As you can imagine,
there are very sensitive

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:58.830
information in board meeting papers,
and this app can manage the

00:05:58.830 --> 00:06:03.350
data protection on them,
you know, security, availability,

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:04.400
et cetera.

00:06:04.490 --> 00:06:11.580
Again, a great example of building an app
to address a very particular niche

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:16.960
industry or niche need that will be well
served by the apps that you produce.

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:21.640
So those are some of the examples
of B2B apps and what they can be.

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:25.350
I'm sure you guys can come up with
some examples right now in your mind

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:29.570
about how you can develop an app
for a particular client or industry.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:37.450
In short,
B2B apps solve a client's specific need.

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:40.770
All right.

00:06:40.770 --> 00:06:45.900
Now that we know what B2B apps are,
let's walk through the process of

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:49.400
delivering them to your end users.

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:52.440
So there are four steps
that you need to go through,

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:54.720
and we'll walk through all of them.

00:06:54.770 --> 00:07:00.100
First, you've got to develop your app,
obviously.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:04.530
After you do that,
you need to submit your app

00:07:04.530 --> 00:07:05.170
to our distribution for us
to distribute your apps.

00:07:06.090 --> 00:07:10.440
Third, you need a way for your
clients to purchase those apps.

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.400
And we'll talk about that.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:19.180
And finally,
you actually have to distribute

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:19.180
these apps to the end users
in your client's organization.

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:24.000
You're responsible for the
first two parts as a developer.

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:26.540
The clients will take care
of the last two parts.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:30.470
But we'll walk through all of them so
that you know what to say to your clients

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:34.480
and you know what you can expect them
to ask you during this whole process.

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:41.920
And it pays to know a little bit
about the distribution method so

00:07:41.930 --> 00:07:41.930
that you can target your app so
that it can be distributed easily.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:43.530
So let's go through them.

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:44.500
All right.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:47.500
Let's talk about developing a B2B app.

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:51.720
Well, for the most part,
developing a B2B app is just

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:54.570
like developing an App Store app.

00:07:55.130 --> 00:08:00.680
You use the same tools,
the same great technologies that we have,

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:05.860
Xcode and the API and the iOS SDK,
same thing.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:07.700
So what's different?

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:10.980
The difference, of course,
is that your apps are

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:13.690
tailored to a specific client.

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:18.230
You're aiming to please a
smaller segment with your app.

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:22.500
So, you might have some custom
look and feel to your app,

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:27.950
You may have to deal with a custom
workflow that your client desires,

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:32.190
and sometimes you have to deal
with server infrastructure that

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:38.490
is custom or peculiar to your
client's business operations.

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:44.600
So here are some strategies that
you can adopt to make your app

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:47.230
more successful as a B2B app.

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:51.310
First, modular, modular, modular, right?

00:08:51.550 --> 00:08:58.390
Design your app in a modular way so that
you can adapt it to your next customer.

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:03.440
So if you have custom views,
make sure they're skinnable or modular.

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:08.590
If you are using a custom backend,
make sure that's modular.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:15.140
Use the Model View Controller design
extensively through your code.

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:21.900
Make sure that both your models and your
views are reusable for the next client.

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:26.300
And here's an interesting tip:
Encapsulate your server protocols.

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:29.550
So if you have a particular
server you're talking to,

00:09:30.210 --> 00:09:34.820
Think about, don't let the protocol
seep in through your code.

00:09:34.910 --> 00:09:38.580
Build an abstraction layer to isolate
that protocol from your model and

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:40.640
your views and your controllers.

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:44.980
So that when you get to the next client,
maybe all you have to do is

00:09:44.980 --> 00:09:48.720
use the same app and have it
talk to a different server.

00:09:49.010 --> 00:09:52.660
And an abstraction layer will help you
to unplug the old server architecture,

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:55.390
plug in the new one, and off you go.

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:58.810
So build modular, modular, modular.

00:10:00.350 --> 00:10:01.800
And here's an interesting note.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:06.050
When you're building an app for a client,
they're entrusting you with

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:08.490
their business information.

00:10:08.690 --> 00:10:13.530
More often than not,
their business information has some kind

00:10:13.630 --> 00:10:17.030
of security stipulation attached to it.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:21.600
So, here's a tip:
build in data security from the start.

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:25.170
Don't wait until the end and
kind of try to work it in.

00:10:25.570 --> 00:10:30.070
Use server authentication to make
sure that whoever is using the app is

00:10:30.070 --> 00:10:31.890
actually authorized to access the data.

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:35.040
Use the keychain.

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:38.700
Do not store passwords
in a plist on disk.

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:39.400
Don't do that.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:41.250
It's a bad idea.

00:10:41.410 --> 00:10:45.540
The keychain is an encrypted
place to store your credentials,

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:49.130
so your passwords, certificates,
identity certificates,

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:51.180
and other kinds of credentials.

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:52.450
So use it.

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:53.720
Use it to your advantage.

00:10:53.870 --> 00:10:58.170
It's got a really nice API,
and it's the best place to

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:01.060
put the secrets in your app.

00:11:01.450 --> 00:11:03.780
and Data Protection.

00:11:04.130 --> 00:11:06.540
Some of you may not be familiar.

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:09.520
may not be familiar with the
data protection technology

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.150
that we offer on iOS.

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:15.300
Data protection on iOS
involves encryption down to

00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:17.700
the block level in Flash.

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:24.160
Using an algorithm that involves the
user's passcode in the encryption.

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:27.560
So until the user types in
their passcode on the device,

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:31.030
it is really,
really hard to read that data on disk.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:35.780
So use data protection and choose
the highest level of data protection

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:39.590
that you can live with in your app,
and you'll be great going forward.

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:43.940
And you'll give your client a
confidence that you're going

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:46.020
to keep their data safe.

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:52.240
And finally, it goes without saying,
collaborate with your client.

00:11:52.290 --> 00:11:55.640
Make sure you understand their needs,
make sure they understand

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:58.700
their workflows,
and build something that can transform

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:02.900
the way that they work and enable them
to do things more efficiently or do

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:05.250
things that couldn't be done before.

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:09.650
So that's all there is to
it for the develop part,

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:10.240
right?

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:14.200
It's basically the same as
developing for an App Store app.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:17.380
Except that you keep in mind that
this is going to be used by a

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:23.250
particular client with specific needs,
and another client may come in a little

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:27.500
while later after your app has been a
big hit and everybody hears about it,

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:32.990
and you better be able to port that
app easily to the second client.

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:34.970
That's the takeaway.

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:39.550
So now that we know how
to develop a B2B app,

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:42.010
let's talk about app submission.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:47.640
Submitting a B2B app is very similar
to submitting an App Store app.

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:49.710
You use iTunes Connect.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:55.950
Except you check this checkbox
here that says this is a B2B app.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:03.290
When you do that,
this form opens up below it.

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:08.310
And here's a place where you
can enter the Apple IDs for the

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:13.500
clients that are allowed to access
this app or to purchase this app.

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:15.400
These are your clients' Apple IDs.

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:19.610
You have to have at least one,
but you can have as many as you want.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:22.690
You can add and remove
Apple IDs over time.

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:23.960
There's no limit.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:29.100
So you can make your app
available to someone and then

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:30.370
not available to them later on.

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:30.370
You can do that.

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:35.270
So only these people that have
their IDs listed here can see

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:39.920
your app in their VPP store,
and your app will not be visible

00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:42.260
in the general app store.

00:13:44.230 --> 00:13:47.360
Next, you select the price tier.

00:13:47.420 --> 00:13:51.970
And this is the price that the
client pays for every license

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:56.350
of your app or every copy of
your app that they purchase.

00:13:56.500 --> 00:14:02.070
Now, some of you are familiar
with our policy on B2B apps.

00:14:02.330 --> 00:14:06.900
We have a $9.99 minimum
price per copy of the app.

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:10.220
Well, today,
I am very excited to announce to

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:12.740
you that we're getting rid of that.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.430
No minimum price.

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:23.990
All tiers are available, including free.

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:32.800
Here are some notes about your B2B app
submissions that you can keep in mind.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:37.250
Number one, once B2B, always B2B.

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:43.170
You cannot take an App Store app and
turn it into a B2B app or vice versa.

00:14:43.340 --> 00:14:46.010
You could submit it multiple
times under different app IDs.

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:48.940
You can have an App Store version
and a B2B version.

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:54.590
But the app ID that you use for a
B2B app will always be a B2B app.

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:58.060
Your app will be reviewed.

00:14:58.230 --> 00:15:04.020
So provide us with a test account
and some login information so that we

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:06.690
can actually login and test your app.

00:15:06.810 --> 00:15:10.660
Now, you might have to work with your
clients to set up some kind of

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:14.380
server account or something,
but we need that so that we can

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:16.740
walk through your app and review it.

00:15:20.050 --> 00:15:22.760
I don't know if you know this,
but B2B apps update just

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:24.790
like app store apps.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:28.240
So when you create an
update to your B2B app,

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:31.110
submit it the same way
that you did before,

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:35.360
you know, specify that this is an
updated binary to that old one,

00:15:35.370 --> 00:15:38.470
and when that gets through
and it gets hosted,

00:15:38.470 --> 00:15:42.180
your clients will see a badge
on their app store icon.

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:46.340
And, you know, it's the same process
that you're familiar with.

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:49.120
You tap update and they
get the updated version.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:50.120
Very straightforward.

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:53.540
It's a great way to deliver
your updates to your clients.

00:15:55.430 --> 00:15:58.680
Now, I don't know if you guys know this,
but promo codes are actually

00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:01.480
available also for B2B apps.

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:04.140
And here's a little trick.

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:10.720
You can give a promo code for
the B2B app to someone who is

00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:10.720
not on the list of Apple IDs.

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:12.840
So let's go through that again.

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:17.580
You can request promo codes for
your apps and give it to someone who

00:16:17.690 --> 00:16:21.260
is not on your list of Apple IDs,
which means that now they

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:22.830
can test drive your app.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:24.400
: Right.

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:28.540
They can download one copy or one
license and test drive your app,

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:29.940
and if they like it, great.

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:34.100
You can add their Apple ID,
and then they can buy it in volume.

00:16:36.130 --> 00:16:39.320
So that's how you submit a B2B app.

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:44.520
It's the same process as
submitting to Apple Store,

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:49.690
to the App Store,
and you check that box that says B2B app.

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:51.320
and go from there.

00:16:51.430 --> 00:16:56.190
Remember that your apps are only visible
to the people that you list on the list.

00:16:57.890 --> 00:17:00.680
All right,
let's move on to what your clients can

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:05.580
do once you've submitted your B2B app
and it's made available in the App Store,

00:17:05.580 --> 00:17:06.900
in the B2B Store.

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:07.790
Purchase.

00:17:07.900 --> 00:17:13.790
The secret to purchasing a B2B app
is the Volume Purchas program.

00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:21.300
This is a program that's available to
any business that has a DUNS number.

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:24.720
And, you know,
most businesses have a DUNS number.

00:17:25.860 --> 00:17:27.860
There's a very easy online setup.

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:29.360
It just takes minutes.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:32.360
You verify online.

00:17:32.360 --> 00:17:36.970
And you get to choose an
Apple ID that the enterprise uses

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:39.600
for purchasing apps in volume.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:41.790
It's really very simple.

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:47.240
You can purchase B2B apps using
the Volume Purchas program,

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:52.550
but you can also purchase App Store apps
at the same price in Volume,

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:56.160
at the same price as the App Store,
and you can buy it in

00:17:56.360 --> 00:17:58.630
any quantity at once.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.660
So let's see what that looks like here.

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:05.160
So this is what your clients will see
when they log into the VPP portal.

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:07.470
They'll see a web page
that says Business Store.

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:09.100
There's a little search bubble up there.

00:18:09.140 --> 00:18:13.660
You can type in any keyword and it
will find the apps in the App Store.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:15.480
But I want to highlight something to you.

00:18:15.730 --> 00:18:19.240
Your B2B apps are highlighted,
highlighted front and

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:20.940
center on their page.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:27.820
So they get to see your apps right
there in their VPP portal page.

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:33.040
So you click on one of those apps,
and this is what you see.

00:18:33.060 --> 00:18:36.870
You get a sheet just like, you know,
the iTunes App Store.

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:41.400
And in that box up there,
they can enter the quantity

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:43.640
that they want to buy.

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:45.620
Click Continue.

00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:48.700
and they've got to pay for it.

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:51.720
We take several forms of payment.

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:52.900
We take credit cards.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.780
We take P cards or procurement cards.

00:18:55.810 --> 00:18:57.850
And we take PayPal.

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:04.040
And at the end of the payment process,
they get a link where they

00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:06.070
can download a spreadsheet.

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:08.160
So let's see what's on
the spreadsheet here.

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:11.700
On the left, these are redemption codes.

00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:14.900
They're like the gift card codes or the
song codes that you're familiar with,

00:19:15.050 --> 00:19:19.700
except they redeem one license
or one copy of your app.

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:26.060
So how many licenses they purchase,
that's how many codes they get.

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:28.600
But look on the right here.

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:31.690
This column has URLs.

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:39.160
that if launched on an iOS device,
will automatically redeem that code.

00:19:39.820 --> 00:19:42.890
And as well,
you can see up there that says redeemed.

00:19:42.900 --> 00:19:45.850
They can track which redemption
codes have been redeemed so over

00:19:45.850 --> 00:19:49.290
time they can see how much they've
consumed and how much they have left.

