00:20:25.210 --> 00:20:27.330
All right.

00:20:27.450 --> 00:20:31.260
So that's how your clients
purchase your B2B app.

00:20:31.330 --> 00:20:34.670
They use the VPP,
the Volume Purchase Program portal.

00:20:34.910 --> 00:20:39.420
Your apps are featured right up front,
and they can buy any volumes they want,

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:42.140
and they get the
redemption codes and URLs.

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:45.890
Now that we know how the
client purchases the app,

00:20:46.210 --> 00:20:50.010
Let's talk a little bit about how
they can distribute those codes

00:20:50.090 --> 00:20:53.100
that they have received from you.

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:55.050
So let's talk about distribution.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:59.840
There are four ways,
four main ways to distribute

00:21:00.020 --> 00:21:02.530
these codes to their end users.

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:06.150
The first, obviously,
is you just type it in.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.300
You type in the code on the device,
you can redeem the code.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:10.560
You're familiar with this.

00:21:10.780 --> 00:21:17.990
It's just like redeeming an iTunes
gift card or a free song card

00:21:17.990 --> 00:21:17.990
that you might have received.

00:21:19.820 --> 00:21:23.740
This is very simple, but, you know,
it takes manual effort.

00:21:23.860 --> 00:21:30.300
The second way to do it is to use
a -- to send the URL to the device.

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:31.960
You can send it using an e-mail.

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:33.940
You can put an e-mail with the URL there.

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:35.400
They tap on it.

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:40.750
They get an app installed.

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:40.750
You can send it via SMS.

00:21:41.540 --> 00:21:43.830
Or here's an interesting way to do it.

00:21:43.910 --> 00:21:48.750
Some enterprises have
created an intranet website.

00:21:48.900 --> 00:22:00.100
[Transcript missing]

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:05.780
The user can tap any of these
app icons and it launches the

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:09.310
URL and that installs the app.

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:16.070
You can put URLs in there
that will install B2B apps

00:22:16.220 --> 00:22:20.630
App Store apps and enterprise
in-house apps that are hosted by

00:22:20.630 --> 00:22:23.600
the enterprise on their own servers.

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:25.260
So it's really convenient.

00:22:25.310 --> 00:22:27.090
A lot of enterprises have done this.

00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:32.370
It's a very easy way for the employees to
browse through all the available apps and

00:22:32.370 --> 00:22:35.100
they'll do the right thing in the end.

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:41.120
A third way of doing this is really cool.

00:22:41.250 --> 00:22:43.700
It's MDM, Mobile Device Management.

00:22:43.810 --> 00:22:50.180
Now, if you don't know what MDM is,
it is an API that allows third-party

00:22:50.270 --> 00:22:56.220
enterprise device management
server to manage a whole bunch

00:22:56.220 --> 00:22:59.400
of iOS devices over the air.

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:03.680
This is really great for enterprises
that want to enroll a lot of people

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:06.100
but don't want to touch every device.

00:23:06.150 --> 00:23:10.600
You have to self-enroll and you
can manage the devices that way.

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:14.900
So using MDM,
you can deliver the redemption

00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:21.600
codes to the device over the air
and in a server-initiated way.

00:23:21.600 --> 00:23:23.380
So here's an example.

00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:27.770
The user will get a pop-up
like this that says,

00:23:27.770 --> 00:23:30.600
"Oh, you got an app coming.

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:32.550
Would you like to install it?"

00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:39.000
You know, the type, tap Install,
enter the Apple ID and password there.

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:42.460
And the app is installed.

00:23:42.540 --> 00:23:44.930
It's super convenient.

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:51.800
As well, if you do this using MDM,
the enterprise has controls about --

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:54.420
that relate to when the apps are removed.

00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:58.300
So they can make a policy that says,
you know, I want to remove this app now.

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:00.120
Just take it off the user's device.

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:02.710
Or say you can set a policy
that says don't back up the

00:24:02.710 --> 00:24:06.270
data in that app because it
contains sensitive information.

00:24:06.310 --> 00:24:09.520
So that excludes that app
from the user's backup set.

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:13.060
A lot of cool things you can do with MDM.

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:18.170
Now the fourth way is one that
maybe not many of you know.

00:24:18.290 --> 00:24:19.230
Maybe you do.

00:24:19.330 --> 00:24:21.810
This is a very popular download.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:23.730
Apple Configurator.

00:24:23.830 --> 00:24:29.860
So Apple Configurator is an app that
we launched about three months ago.

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:33.900
And it has been met with great welcome.

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:39.780
It is a way to configure a
lot of iOS devices at once.

00:24:40.430 --> 00:24:44.220
and to manage them over time.

00:24:44.270 --> 00:24:45.980
Right?

00:24:46.010 --> 00:24:48.600
It's USB only,
but you can plug a whole bunch

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:50.760
of them at the same time.

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:53.980
And it can do really cool things.

00:24:54.020 --> 00:24:56.460
It can activate your device.

00:24:56.530 --> 00:24:58.260
It can configure it.

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:01.680
It can install apps on it.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:08.380
And you can use that as an unboxing tool
for an enterprise purchased equipment.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:15.360
And you can also set it up so that when
the device is again seen on the USB port,

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:19.990
it restores the configuration
on the device to a known state.

00:25:20.260 --> 00:25:22.200
Right, so that's great for retail,
for example.

00:25:22.200 --> 00:25:25.590
You hand out something to the floor,
it comes back,

00:25:25.590 --> 00:25:28.900
it gets restored to a known state.

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:33.810
So, Apple Configurator is really cool,
and I want to highlight this today

00:25:33.830 --> 00:25:38.420
because there are some modes of
operation that may give you some ideas

00:25:38.930 --> 00:25:43.600
about B2B apps that you might develop,
because it allows the iOS device

00:25:43.600 --> 00:25:47.670
to be used in situations that you
might not have thought of before.

00:25:47.870 --> 00:25:51.310
So let's go through that and
see if you agree with me.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:53.040
Let's talk about Apple Configurator.

00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:56.730
So this is what you see when
you launch Apple Configurator.

00:25:57.410 --> 00:26:00.510
As you can see,
there are three main silos here.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:03.830
In general,
there are three major categories

00:26:03.830 --> 00:26:07.630
of things that you can do
with Apple Configurator.

00:26:07.720 --> 00:26:11.820
On the left, you have Prepare Devices.

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:15.220
Like I said,
you can set up a configuration,

00:26:15.670 --> 00:26:20.130
unbox your device, plug it in,
puts the configuration in there,

00:26:20.130 --> 00:26:25.130
puts Wi-Fi in there, VPN, whatever,
restrictions on the device.

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:31.360
It installs apps, automatically redeems
app codes on the device.

00:26:31.460 --> 00:26:33.530
Very convenient for that.

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:36.260
In the middle column, there's Supervised.

00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:43.600
Now, Supervised devices is something that
we introduced in 5.0 and in iOS 5.0,

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:47.440
and we have enhanced greatly in iOS 6.0.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:51.730
Supervised devices are
basically company-owned

00:26:52.550 --> 00:26:58.010
devices that you can control to
a greater extent than you could

00:26:58.450 --> 00:27:00.640
and I will be talking about how
you can bring your own device.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:06.780
And we'll talk about that
in a few slides down,

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:06.780
but it's a very cool mode that
you can put your iOS device into.

00:27:07.140 --> 00:27:09.280
And finally, there's assign.

00:27:09.340 --> 00:27:11.500
Assign devices is also very cool.

00:27:11.550 --> 00:27:17.000
You can actually associate a user
profile with an arbitrary device.

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.620
So,
let me talk about that a little bit more.

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:24.800
Let's say you have a classroom
and you have a pool of iPads.

00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:27.080
A student checks out an iPad.

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:27.650
Uses it.

00:27:27.650 --> 00:27:29.200
Brings it back to the pool.

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:31.470
When the iPad is brought
back to the pool,

00:27:31.470 --> 00:27:36.500
configurator will grab all the app
data and configuration from that

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:39.890
iPad and store it on his hard drive.

00:27:40.770 --> 00:27:45.000
When the student comes back the next
time and checks out a different iPad,

00:27:45.320 --> 00:27:51.600
Configurator takes that configuration
and puts it back on the new iPad.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:54.970
So it's as though they got the same iPad,
but it's not really.

00:27:54.990 --> 00:27:58.210
It's a different iPad that
looks exactly the same as

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:00.600
their iPad from the day before.

00:28:00.710 --> 00:28:04.190
So this is great where you have to
have a check-in/check-out system.

00:28:04.580 --> 00:28:07.870
So in some environments,
you have to assign a device to

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:10.070
somebody who's responsible for it.

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:12.910
At the end of the day, check it back in.

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:15.900
But they don't want to
buy an iPad for everyone.

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:18.740
So this is a great solution for that.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:21.160
All right.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:25.810
So as you can see,
Apple configurator is good for managing,

00:28:25.860 --> 00:28:28.940
is great for managing a
lot of devices at once.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:30.820
Mass configuration.

00:28:30.820 --> 00:28:35.280
Here's an example where these
are actually iPod touches.

00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:38.360
In a retail environment,
you check it out,

00:28:38.430 --> 00:28:42.280
use it on the sales floor,
end of the day, bring it back.

00:28:42.480 --> 00:28:44.650
The configuration is restored.

00:28:44.650 --> 00:28:48.400
As it's recharging,
it can be used the next day.

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:51.400
Now, imagine your app running there.

00:28:51.400 --> 00:28:55.430
So that's a new opportunity
for you as B2B developers.

00:29:00.900 --> 00:29:05.700
Apple Configurator can also manage
your app distribution for you.

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:08.930
So Apple Configurator can
import that spreadsheet that

00:29:09.020 --> 00:29:10.700
you saw a few slides back.

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:12.610
They'll import it in.

00:29:12.930 --> 00:29:14.400
It installs the apps automatically.

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:17.010
You can tell it, you know,
every time I plug in a device,

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:18.490
install these apps, done.

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:21.090
It will do it as you plug it in.

00:29:21.380 --> 00:29:24.460
And here's an interesting
thing that it can do that you

00:29:24.460 --> 00:29:26.540
can only do on Configurator.

00:29:26.590 --> 00:29:30.430
It can redeem your app codes,
your redemption codes,

00:29:30.430 --> 00:29:34.290
against the device instead
of against an Apple ID.

00:29:34.780 --> 00:29:36.590
All right, let me say that again.

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:45.020
It can redeem your app redemption
code on a per-device manner,

00:29:45.020 --> 00:29:50.500
not on a per-Apple ID manner,
which means you don't have to

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:50.500
put an Apple ID on the devices.

00:29:57.450 --> 00:30:02.410
This is really powerful for no-touch
installation and for retail or education

00:30:02.760 --> 00:30:09.020
or healthcare environments or hospitality
where you don't really want to type

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:11.500
things in on a screen to install an app.

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:14.420
All right.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:16.270
So supervised devices,
let's talk about that.

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:18.100
It's really cool.

00:30:18.340 --> 00:30:21.870
Supervised devices are
enterprise-owned devices,

00:30:22.290 --> 00:30:22.480
right?

00:30:23.200 --> 00:30:24.730
In contrast to bring your own device.

00:30:24.910 --> 00:30:29.240
So this is devices that are
bought by a company for its use.

00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:33.400
You can only supervise
a device at activation.

00:30:33.850 --> 00:30:38.260
Right, so you have to erase the device
or something or unbox it,

00:30:38.300 --> 00:30:41.350
activate it into a supervised state.

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:46.920
A supervised device will
not pair with iTunes,

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:50.140
which is a big deal in some cases.

00:30:50.270 --> 00:30:55.780
It will only talk to the computer
or the host that supervised it.

00:30:58.220 --> 00:31:02.680
Once you supervise a device,
you get access to a whole list of

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:06.280
capabilities that were not there before.

00:31:06.330 --> 00:31:09.010
Global HTTP Proxy, for one.

00:31:09.330 --> 00:31:13.420
You can funnel all the
HTTP and HTTPS traffic on the

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:16.360
device through a single proxy.

00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:19.700
Important for education,
important for healthcare.

00:31:19.820 --> 00:31:26.300
iBookstore, iMessage,
and Game Center from your device.

00:31:26.430 --> 00:31:30.570
And you'd like this one,
you can prevent app removal.

00:31:34.900 --> 00:31:38.290
With supervised devices,
you have access to a really

00:31:38.290 --> 00:31:44.910
cool mode that we introduced in
iOS 6.0 called Single App Mode.

00:31:50.700 --> 00:31:57.060
This is a mode where the app takes
over the entire device experience.

00:31:57.060 --> 00:31:59.850
You cannot exit it using the home button.

00:31:59.950 --> 00:32:02.290
If you power it,
if you reboot the device,

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:04.100
it comes back to that app.

00:32:04.100 --> 00:32:05.700
You can't get out of it.

00:32:05.700 --> 00:32:09.130
You can get out of it by plugging
it back into the configurator

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:11.100
and taking it out of that mode.

00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:13.700
So here's a good example
for single app mode.

00:32:13.700 --> 00:32:17.840
It's a sales floor application,
so people can browse a sales catalog

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:20.000
right in the retail environment.

00:32:20.190 --> 00:32:23.430
You know people like to push buttons.

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:26.440
And now you can lock
them into the app and,

00:32:26.440 --> 00:32:31.290
you know, you'll be assured that
there's no way out of the app.

00:32:31.360 --> 00:32:34.180
Single app mode, really powerful.

00:32:34.230 --> 00:32:36.190
Your app could be there.

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:40.960
So I would like to invite
right now Todd Fernandez,

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:47.000
the project manager for the configurator,
Apple configurator, to give you a little

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:48.940
demo of what it can do.

00:32:48.940 --> 00:32:48.940
Todd?

00:32:53.900 --> 00:34:50.000
[Transcript missing]

00:34:50.180 --> 00:34:55.100
And this is where if you have
devices that are out on a duty cycle,

00:34:55.100 --> 00:34:59.430
whether they're going to guests in
a museum or a restaurant or hotel,

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:03.150
or maybe retail point of sale systems,
where a shared device is used by a

00:35:03.150 --> 00:35:06.310
guest or an employee and then comes
back and you want to make sure it's

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:09.460
in the right state before it goes
out to the next guest or employee.

00:35:09.890 --> 00:35:15.630
Configurator will do that
automatically when you reconnect

00:35:15.630 --> 00:35:15.630
the device via USB to that Mac.

00:35:16.570 --> 00:35:19.900
And finally, building on top of those
shared supervised devices,

00:35:20.100 --> 00:35:23.970
